y, but it's transitive. No Docker needed, so being concise is key.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"advisory_preparation\",\n  \"summary\": \"OGNL is an in-process expression language; the resolved 3.3.5 artifact only needs its normal transitive Javassist dependency and no Docker service, but meaningful reflective-access coverage relies on JVM/test setup already present in the existing scaffold.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"Keep OGNL tests in-process against local POJOs/OgnlContext/OgnlRuntime. Preserve JVM test args for strong encapsulation, at least `--add-opens=java.base/java.lang=ALL-UNNAMED`; upstream 3.3.5's JDK17 profile also opens `java.base/java.util`. Only set OGNL system properties inside tests that intentionally cover those switches, especially `ognl.UseJDK9PlusAccessHandler`, `ognl.security.manager`, and `ognl.UseFirstMatchGetSetLookup`; restore them after each test because OgnlRuntime reads several at class initialization. On JDK 25, do not assume `System.setSecurityManager` succeeds; guard SecurityManager-specific coverage for `SecurityException`/`UnsupportedOperationException` or assert the non-installed path.\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"The Java-run failure for 3.3.5 reproduces as a behavioral assertion failure in existing ObjectPropertyAccessor coverage, not as a missing dependency or external service.\",\n    \"Javassist is a compile/runtime transitive dependency of `ognl:ognl:3.3.5`; adding it explicitly is unnecessary unless local Gradle resolution proves otherwise.\",\n    \"SecurityManager and `sun.misc.Unsafe` paths are fragile on JDK 25 and later, so tests should avoid depending on successful SecurityManager installation.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_02f28fec45c0f2e4016a40e48a6f648197a78f27a217b2b185\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 8442, "output": 887, "cacheRead": 63488, "cacheWri